The paper deals with the computational complexity of computing an Arrow-Debreu market equilibrium, which is a problem in computational game theory and computational economics. Therefore, cs.GT (Game Theory) is the most likely sub-category. The problem is shown to be PPAD-complete, which is a class of problems related to the complexity of finding fixed points in continuous mappings, and hence cs.CC (Computational Complexity) is also a likely sub-category. The proof involves constructing a reduction from a variant of the Nash equilibrium problem, which is a problem in algorithmic game theory, and hence cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) are also likely sub-categories. Finally, the problem is related to market equilibria, which is a topic in microeconomics, and hence cs.EC (Economics and Computation) is also a likely sub-category.
